snippet.textDisplay:
Hey, I just wanted to give everyone a bit of historical insight as to why people are referring to those piano chords in the beginning as "Japanese Jazz" - it's not entirely baseless, and in fact it's a very interesting subject.


In the 80s, after the Japanese economic boom, Japan began to explore, adopt, and adapt Western music and these new, exotic styles grew incredibly popular there.
However, they didn't focus only on the modern "New Wave" sound of the mainstream at the time, but indeed explored genres as varied as jazz and bossa nova.

Recently, with the rise of lo-fi production, and a waxing interest in Japanese culture,recordings from this period of Japanese music have become very popular, because in essence they are bossa nova, jazz, bebop, etc songs but recorded with technology decades newer than the popular records in the west, and often with a distinct original flair. Sometimes, an individual today might first learn of Bossa Nova through Japanese records from the 80s and 90s!

An example of an artist that demonstrates some of what I'm talking about is Kazumi Yasui. (https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=drcTCpNZ0BE) You'll hear familiar bossa nova elements infused with hints of japanese instrumentation. :)

snippet.textDisplay:
As a musician myself, I can't thank you enough for sharing these words. To be very honest, I've almost quit music myself, and I've become heavily depressed, anxiety, having suicidal thoughts quite often, and even to the point of having an existential crisis. Perhaps some of you can also relate: reality is cruel & cold, and it often crushed down our dreams. I can even understand now why there are people who are depressed & suicidal in this life.

But it's really, really rare indeed, when a popular artist/musician's words really touch you deeply, when you need the most. I'm glad that at least, these words have somewhat just sparked even just a tiny little bit of motivation, hope, and most importantly perhaps, speaks deeply into my soul, which have been so weary, and to be very honest, almost giving up on life too.

Again, thank you very much for sharing this. January turned out to be just another depressing failure for me personally, but just as I feel hopeless, hopefully, after reading & soaking in these words, this month of February will be the real new start of something better for me (and also for anyone who's currently also struggling with depression & harsh reality).

- from Indonesia -

It’s actually pretty close to my philosophy of what I want to achieve when writing my own music.

Your work already stirred our souls, and will continue to do so :)
